<section id="position">
  <header>
    <h2>Position</h2>
  </header>

  <p><strong>Focal positioning</strong> lets you steer which part of an image stays visible when it’s cropped. Apply positional classes to the gallery or individual images so key subjects remain in frame—handy for portraits, product shots, or artwork with important edges.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<ul class="gallery image-cover huge">
			<li>
				<figure>
					<img class="left-top" src="/images/sandrart.jpg" alt="">
					<figcaption>X: 0%, Y: 0%</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</li>
			<li>
				<figure>
					<img class="center-top" src="/images/sandrart.jpg" alt="">
					<figcaption>X: 50%, Y: 0%</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</li>
			<li>
				<figure>
					<img class="right-top" src="/images/sandrart.jpg" alt="">
					<figcaption>X: 100%, Y: 0%</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</li>
		</ul>



		<ul class="gallery image-cover huge">
			<li>
				<figure>
					<img class="left-top" src="/images/1878_Frederick_Leighton_-_Nausicaa.jpg" alt="">
					<figcaption>X: 0%, Y: 50%</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</li>
			<li>
				<figure>
					<img class="left-center" src="/images/1878_Frederick_Leighton_-_Nausicaa.jpg" alt="">
					<figcaption>X: 0%, Y: 50%</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</li>
			<li>
